{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604677/1946012101/0145.xml":{"full_text":"Veteran Benefits\nOne of Largest\nItems in Budget\nBy ROBERT BRUSKIN.\nDescribing veterans' pensions and\nbenefits as \"one of the largest sin\ngle categories in the Federal Budg\net,\u201d President Truman today asked\nCongress to appropriate $4,787,000,\n000 for this purpose during the next\nfiscal year.\nPensions alone will cost $1,748,000,\n000. President Truman declared\nthat \u201ctwo-thirds of this amount will\nbe received by veterans of the war\nwhich we have just won.\u201d\n\u201cEverlasting tribute and gratitude\nwill be paid by all Americans to\nthose brave men who did not come\nback, who will never come back\u2014the\n330.000 who died that the Nation\nmight live and progress,\" Mr. Tru\nman said in his message to Con\ngress.\n\u201cAll Americans will also remain\ndeeply conscious of the obligation\nowed to that large number of sol\ndiers, sailors and marines who suf\nfered wounds and sickness in their\nservice. They may be certain that\ntheir sacrifice will never be forgot\nten or their needs neglected.\u201d\nVeteran Agency Fund Doubled.\nTo assure efficient functioning of\nthe harried Veterans\u2019 Administra\ntion, he asked that it be given more\nthan twice the amount it had in\n1946; $557,287,000 as compared with\n$227,675,000.\nThis amount provides for medical\ncare and operation of 103,000 hos\npital and domiciliary beds at a cost\nof $260,000,000. A separate appro\npriation is sought to provide 13,000\nhospital beds as part of the con\nstruction recently authorized by\nCongress. The estimate for this\ncost, $120,000,000, was shown in the\nbudget as part of the general public\nworks program.\nAlso included in the funds for\nthe Veterans\u2019 Administration, Mr,\nTruman said, were provisions for\ntuition expenses and maintenance\nallowances for a half million veter\nans who are students.\nMr. Truman recommended that\nCongress increase veterans\u2019 unem\nployment benefits from $20 to $25 a\nweek at an additional cost of $220,\n000,000 for 1947. Unemployment at\npresent financial payments is ex\npected to total $850,000,000 during\nveterans' readjustment periods in\nthe next year.\nHousing Action Asked.\nMr. Truman called for \"a realistic:\nand practical attack\u201d on the hous\ning emergency for veterans, declar\ning it \u201cwill require aggressive\naction by local governments, with\nFederal aid. to exploit all oppor\ntunities and to give the veterans as\nfar as possible first chance at\nvacancies.\"\n\u201cIt will require continuation of\nrent control in shortage areas as\nwell as legislation to permit control\nof sales prices. It will require\nmaximum conversion of temporary\nwar units for veterans\u2019 housing and1\ntheir transportation to communities\nwith their mast pressing needs.\u201d\nThe ultimate benefit, he added,\nwhich veterans receive from loan\nguarantees depends on restraining\nbuilding costs and real estate\nvalues from inflation. To pay the\ncosts of the loan program for veter\nans on reasonably valued proper\nties, he asked for $21,000,000.\nMessage\n(Continued From First Page.)\nnonagricultural and nongovern\nmental establishments, have re\nceived increases\u2014generally from 10\nto 15 per cent\u2014since August 15, the\nday after Japan capitulated, the\nmessage amplified.\nIncidentally, the President for the\nfirst time committed himself to a\nspecific figure for boosting the 40\ncent rate of the minimum wage\nlaw, saying he favored a projected!\n65-70-75-cent scale.\nDespitg the stride wave. President\nTruman injected a note of optimism\nin his message. He said that \u2018\u2018for'\nthe immediate future, the business\nprospects are generally so favorable\nthat there is danger of such fever\nish and opportunistic activity that\ngrave postwar problems may be\nneglected.\u201d Again, while conceding\nthat \"any precise appraisal of the\neconomic outlook at this time is\nparticularly difficult,\u201d the President\nsaid that \u201cin general, the outlook\nfor business is good, and is likely to\ncontinue good\u2014provided we control\ninflation and achieve peace in man\nagement-labor relations.\u201d\nPledges Small Business Aid.\nReviewing business prospects, the\nPresident spoke of his hope to en\ncourage industrial expansion in\nWest and South and said he was\nasking the Secretaries of Agricul\nture. Commerce and Labor \u201cto ex\nplore jointly methods for stimulat\ning new industries, particularly in\nareas with surplus labor.\u201d He\npledged financial aid to small busi\nness, along with strict trust law en\nfnrppmpnt t n Oil rVv mnnon/vUni.\nFurther, on the job front, the\nmessage disclosed that approximate\nly $1,740,000,000 will be spent on I\nFederal public works and for loans\nand grants to States and municipal\nities for public works next year.\nThe budget is based on a prospec\ntive national income of $140.000,000.-!\n000 for the year. Describing inflation\nas \"our greatest immediate domestic!\nproblem,\" President Truman re\nnewed his argument for re-enact-;\nment of rent and price control laws1\nand the Second War Powers Act\u2014\nwhich includes allocation powers\u2014to\ncarry them beyond next June 30.\n\u201cIf we expect to maintain a steady!\neconomy we shall have to maintain\nprice and rent control for many\nmonths to come,\" he said. \"The in\nflationary pressures on prices and\nrents, with relatively few exceptions,'\nare now^at an all-time peak. Unless\nthe Price Control Act is renewed,\nthere will be no limit to which our\nprice levels would soar. Our country\nwould face national disaster.\"\n\u2022Budget in New Form.\nAa a complementary proposal to\nextension of price control for a year.\nMr. Truman urged the continuation\nof food subsidies, explaining that\nthe expected drop in prices had!\n.failed to materialize after the war.\nand \u201cfood prices are pressing hard\nagainst the ceilings.\" An 8 per cent\nfood price rise was held out as the;\npossibles alternative to continuing!\nsubsidies beyond the contemplated1\nexpiration date of June 30.\nThe new budget is shaped on dif\nferent lines than those of other\nyears. vThe $35,860,000,000 approved\nby the President covers not only\nitems for which there already is\nstatutory authority, but includes\nalso approximately $4,000,000,000 for\nproposed programs, which would\nipean that if Congress failed to\nback any of these, expenditures\nwould be reduced by that much. In\nother years supplemental appro\npriations have been asked for such\nItems after the regular budget was\n\u2022ubmitted.\nThis $4,000,000,000 would care for\nsuch outlays as international com\nmitments, the projected Govern\nment pay-raise and some national\ndefense projects.\nThis first postwar budget com\npares with the $67,229,000,000 being\nexpended this year after the col\nlapse of Japan in August permitted\noriginal estimates to be scaled down.\nIt is about a third of the size of the\nwartime budgets\u2014the $100,000,000,\n000 of 1945, for example\u2014but still\nruns four times as high as the pre\nwar budget of 1940.\n13 Billions for Army, Navy.\nDefense, war and war liquidation\naccount for approximately $15,000,\n000,000. The \"aftermath\" of war\ncovers about $11,000,000,000 more, in\ncluding $5,000,000,000 for interest on\nthe public debt; $4,208,000,000 for\nveterans\u2019 benefits and pensions, a\nboost of nearly a billion dollars, and\n$1,600,000,000 for tax refunds.\nThe President, commenting on the\nwar expenditure, conceded that\nSI5,000,000,000\u2014Army and Navy will\nneed $13,000,000,000\u2014is a large sum\n\u201cfor a year which begins 10 months\nafter fighting has ended,\u2019\u2019 being 10\ntimes the amount of nrewnr riefpnsp\nbudgets. However, he added, \"this\nestimate reflects the immense job\nthat is involved in winding up a\nglobal war effort and stresses the\ngreat responsibilty that victory has\nplaced on this country.\"\nThe President said for that the\n\u201cslowly rising trend\u201d in general gov\nernmental expenditures which be\ngan in 1943 again would be in evi\ndence, amplifying that the Govern\nment is larger than it was before\nthe war because its responsibilities\nhave increased. He cited aids to\nagriculture, social security and gen\neral public works as contributing\nfactors in this trend.\nNevertheless, President Truman\nadded, economies can be effected\nthrough efficient operation and he\nexpects to make gains in this direc\ntion by using the powers of the new\nReorganization Act.\n\u201cNot Time\" to Cut Taxes.\nDiscussing the public debt, the\nPresident said it is a problem re\nquiring consideration,* but that it\ncan be handled.\nOn taxes, he pointed out that the\neffect of the recent reductions will\nnot be felt until the fiscal year 1948.\nDeclaring the administration's in\ntention to protect the financial\nstructure of the country, the Presi\ndent added:\nit is gooa to move toward a bal\nanced budget and a start on the re\ntirement of debt at a time when\ndemand for goods is strong and the\nbusiness outlook is good. These con\nditions prevail today. Business is\ngood and there are still powerful\nforces working in the direction of\ninflation. This is not the time for\ntax reduction.\u201d\nThe President ended his message\nwith a plea for national unity.\nFlaying \"voices which foster fear\nand suspicion and intolerance and\nhate,\" Mr. Truman said that \u201cthey\nhave become busy again.\u201d\n\"They must not prevail,\u201d he\nwarned.\nNew Budget Stresses\nDevelopment of U. S.\nNatural Resources\nPresident Truman's budget mes\nsage today\u2014in marked contrast to\nthose submitted to Congress during\nthe war years\u2014laid emphasis on de\nvelopment of the national resources!\nof the United States and its terri\ntories. Good roads and the develop-!\nment 6f hydroelectric power received\nspecial attention.\nThe President asked Congress to\n;tart a $10,000,000 highway program\nn Alaska with an initial appropria\nion of $2,300,000 for roads, bridges\nind trails, to be expended during\nflie 1946-47 fiscal year. Included1\nivas $1,000,000 for continuing work\nm the Richardson Highway.\nMindful of the return of Indians\nfrom war work and the armed forces\nto their reservations, the President\nasked $41,393,515, an increase of\n514.000.000 over last year\u2019s appro\npriation, for the Office of Indian\nAffairs to promote education, agri\nculture- and other benefits.\nSynthetic Fuel Program.\nIncluded in the budget also was\na request for $4,190,320 for the Bu\nreau of Mines to carry on its syn\nthetic fuel program, primarily from\ncoal and oil shale. Also provided\nwere $2,400,000 for the investigation\nand development of mineral de\nposits ana $202,000 for helium re\ncoorph a nH rnv>ratinn rtf nrocent\nhelium plants.\nFor protection and development of\nthe Nation's timberlands, the Presi\ndent asked a $10,000,000 increase for\nthe United States Forest Service,\nmaking a total budget of $38,251,\n500. The amount included $3,000.\n000 for Government purchase of pri\nvate forest lands.\nAn $80,000,000 appropriation was\nasked by the President for three big\nhydroelectric power agencies\u2014the j\nTennessee Valley Authority, the\nBonneville project and the South\nwestern Power Administration. The\nfunds provide for the construction\nof 600 miles of transmission lines\nand 14 substations in connection\nwith the big Bonneville plant in\nthe Northwest.\nFlood Control Planned.\nThe President informed Congress\nthat the administration was work\ning on plans for flood control and\nhydroelectric developments in the\nMissouri Valley, the Arkansas Val\nley and the Central Valley of Cali\nfornia.\nAnticipating a rapid rise in visitors\nto America's great public parks, the.\nPresident asked an appropriation\nof $32,643,215 for the National Park\nService to enable it to prepare for\nthis influx. During the war, he\nsaid the parks have been on a vir\ntual maintenance basis. The cur\nrent appropriation includes $22,400,\n000 for the improvement of roads\nand trails and $2,500,000 for tourist\nfacilities.\nAppropriation of $212,720,000 for\nriver and harbor improvements and\n$110,000,000 for flood control was\nrecommended. In addition, he asked\n$4,815,000 for planning river and\nharbor projects and $4,815,000 for\nflood-control blue-printing. The ap\npropriations. he said, will permit a\nstart on the Florida barge canal.\nThe protection and increase of\nwildlife would be promoted under\na $12,508,275 appropriation requested\nfor the Fish and Wildlife Service,\nan increase of $2,000,000 over last\nyear. Included in the sum is $858,000\nfor protecting the important Alas\nkan fisheries.\nLeopold Plea Rejected\nLONDON, Jan. 21 OP).\u2014The Brus\nsels radio said today that the Bel\ngian government had rejected a re\nquest by King Leopold that the\nquestion of his return to the throne\nbe submitted to a national referen\ndum following the forthcoming\ngeneral elections. Leopold now is\nin Switzerland.\n\nNineteen American cities have\ninter-American centers to foster in\nterest in nations south of the border.\nChavez Would Delay\nFEPC for Legislation\nOf 'Importance'\nBy the Associated Press.\nSenator Chavez, Democrat, of\nNew Mexico, whose motion called\nthe fair employment practice bill\nup for debate, has expressed willing\nness to have the measure put aside\nfor \u2018any important legislation.\u201d\n\"If any Senate committee reports\nany important legislation for action\nI am willing to put aside the FEPC\nbill,\u201d Senator Chavez said. \"By im\nportant legislation I mean any labor\nlegislation or bills dealing with de\nmobilization or other matters.\n\"We ought to vote FEPC up or\ndown now. There are sufficient\nvotes in the Senate to pass it. It is\nthe only legislation requested by the\nPresident which is ready for action.\nBut, I am not one to delay or inter\nfere with any important legislation.\u201d\nThe Southern filibuster against\nthe FEPC bill, meanwhile, became\nofficial today when Senator Bilbo.\nDemocrat, of Mississippi announced\nhis intention to speak indefinitely.\nWinding a muffler carefully\naround his fabulous sound-box,\nSenator Bilbo submitted to an in\ncei view'.\n\"Why, ves,\u201d he said. \u201cIt so hap\npens that I do intend to speak 30\ndays or so.\n\"But I am only one of many. We\nhave about 25 Senators on our\nvarsity team, all of them primed to\ntalk.\n\"If the opposition wants to run\n24 hours a day, we are abso-100\nper-cent-lutely ready.\n\"We have enough speakers so we\ncan operate in shifts.\"\nReady With Blueprints.\nHis reference was to a plan pro\nposed by Senators Chavez and\nMorse. Republican, of Oregon to\nhold the Senate in continuous ses\nsion in the hope of forcing a vote.\nRiffling merrily through a sheaf\nof reference notes, P^arl River\nCounty's free-style talking champ\ndisclosed that he has finished the\nblueprints for his opening remarks.\n\u201cThe first part of my speech,\u201d\nSenator Bilbo confided, \u201cwill be\ndevoted exclusively to the virtue*\nand accomplishments of filibustering\nfrom 1789 to the present time.\"\nThe Mississippian added that be\ncause he has so many other*sub\njects to discuss, it is hardly likely\nhe will get around to reading pas\nsages from his new book, to be pub\nlished in March. A treatise on race\nrelations, It is entitled \u201ctake your\nchoice\u2014separation or mongreiiza\ntion.\"\nChance to Relax.\nProspects were that the South\nerners could relax an hour or so to\nday and let the reading clerk do\ntheir work. It Is the clerk's task to\ndrone out the President\u2019s combined\nlengthy message on the state of the\nUnion and the budget.\nWhen that is over, however, op\nponents of the FEPC bill plan to get\noacK on rneir work, mat work, be\ngun Friday, is discussion of improve\nments and corrections in Thursday's\nofficial journal.\nThe bill that touched off the fili\nbuster is a measure to create a\npermanent FEPC to replace the war\ntime agency charged with guarding\nagainst job discrimination.\nD. C. Vote\n_'Continued From First Page.)\nwords, to indorse the joint resolu\ntion.\nThese joint sponsors of the resolu\ntion were followed by other congres\nsional champions of District suf\nfrage. and by leaders in the Board\nof Trade, Fedeiation of Citizens\u2019\nAssociations, the Citizens Joint Com\nmittee on National Representation,\nthe new Central Suffrage Confer\nence. and civic leaders who praised\nand welcomed the President's mes\nsage.\nSticks to Senate Stand.\nPresident Truman was said by\nMelvin D. Hildreth, vice chairman\nof the Democratic Central Commit\ntee of the District, to have followed\nwith great consistency his action as\na Senator from Missouri when he\nadvocated District suffrage as a\nmember of the Platform Committee\nat the last Democratic National\nConvention.\n'This is the first time a President\nof the United States ever officially\nrecommended to Congress that the\ncitizens of the District should have\na vote,\u201d said Mr. Hildreth, who was\na member of the Platform Commit\ntee fighting for the suffrage plank.\nThe plank in the Democratic plat\nform definitely placed the party on\nrecord in favor of suffrage for Dis\ntrict residents.\nIt said:\n\u201cWe favor the extension of the\nright of suffrage to the people of\nthe District of Columbia.\u201d\nFirst Since Jackson.\nPresident Truman s official com\nmunication to Coneress follmueH hie\nrecent press conference declaration\nin favor of suffrage here. At that\ntime it was pointed out that it was\nthe first time since President An\ndrew Jackson\u2019s term of office that a\nChief Executive had come out for\nDistrict suffrage. Jackson, who was\nPresident from 1829 to 1837, sug\ngested no more than a District\ndelegate in the House. At that time\nWashington was scarcely more than\na village.\nComment on the Truman message\nincluded the following:\nSenator Capper\u2014\"His words have\nmy unqualified approval. I think the\nPresident has said better, in a few\nwords, what we who favor national\nrepresentation have been trying to\nsay for so long. In fact, his is the\nbest statement of the problem in a\nfew words I have ever heard; he has\nput it all in a nutshell. I think his\nwords will assure the success of the\nfight for the vote within a veryffew\nmonths. This should be very help\nful in bringing about favorable ac\ntion in Congress. The president has\nrendered a great service in empha\nsizing the fact of a voteless District\nof Columbia.\u201d\nRepresentative Sumners\u2014\"I cer\ntainly approve his statement, be\ncause residents of the District\nshould not be denied the right to\nparticipate in their national affairs.\nRepresentation in Congress and the\nright to vote for President and Vice\nPresident is what the District needs,\nand what I hope the President\nthinks it needs.\u201d\nRepresentative Randolph, Demo\ncrat, of West Virginia, former chair\nman of District Committee and\nChairman of Civil Affairs Commit\ntee, \u201cThe President very prop\nerly focuses attention on the prin\nciple of suffrage for those within\nthe District of Columbia. It is a\nprinciple so right that we wonder\nwhy words and not action, year in\nand year out, are expressed on this\nsubject. It shall be my purpose,\nwithin the scope of my individual\nand legislative jurisdiction, to con\ntinue vigorously the crusade for\nnot only the right but the responsi\nbility of the franchise.\"\nJohn Russell Young, president o\nthe District Commissioners: \u201cPres\nident Truman's recommendatioi\nshould greatly hearten all of u\nwho have been asking for the righ\nwhich is due every American citizen\n\u201cHis official approval of Distric\nsuffrage at this particular timi\nshould be a great spur to th\nmovement which has been unde\nway, so patiently and so long. Pros\npects for success now are bette:\nthan ever. There is no doubt ii\nmy mind that the President's word,\ndefinitely can be Interpreted a\ndirect support for the Sumners'\nCapper resolution.\u201d\nJesse C. Suter, vice chairman\nCitizens' Joint Committee on Na\ntlonal Representation, and vici\nchairman of the Board of Tradi\nCommittee on National Represents\ntion:\n\u201cThe President\u2019s statement shoulc\ngive powerful stimulus to the move\nment for national representation a\nembodied in the pending Sumners\nci leauiuuuu iui a cuiisiliu\ntional amendment, empowerini\nCongress to grant to citizens of thi\nDistrict of Columbia representation\nin Congress and the electoral college\n\u2018\u2018The franchise of citizens of thi\nUnited States, now denied to citi\nzens of Washington, is the right o\nvoting representation in the Ameri\ncan Government\u2014a right which thi\nSumners-Capper resolution is de\nsigned to restore, without impair\ning the constitutional status of thi\nDistrict of Columbia as the seat o\nGovernment under the control o\nCongress.\u201d\nWilbur S. Finch, president of th<\nFederation of Citizens' Association:\nand acting chairman of the newly\nformed Central Suffrage Confer\nence: \u2018\u2018As clear cut a statement a;\nyou can find for complete suflfrag*\nfor the District. As I interpret it\nit means representation for the Dis\ntrict in Congress and the right t<\nvote for President as well as mu\nnicipal self-government. It is\nmost heartening development.\n\u201cIf the President had mentionei\nonly municipal self-government, i\nwould have meant that he only fa\nj vored the District having the vot\nto choose its city officials. But h\nwent much farther than that. B\nasking for a greater measure o\nlocal self-government, in my mini\njthe President meant that the Dis\ntrict had the right to have its own\nrepresentatives in Congress, th\nsame as other cities have repre\nsentation in their State Legisla\ntures. The Congress of the Unitei\nO i _ 1 i i a\nULgiOiatUl\nand local sell-government would no\nbe complete unless we had the righ\nto select our representatives ii\nCongress and to vote for the Presi\ndent of the United States.\u201d\nSefton Darr, chairman of thi\nSteering Committee of the Centra\nSuffrage Conference: \u201dA fine state\nment. By asking that citizens not bi\ndenied their franchise merely be\ncause they live in Washington, Presi\ndent Truman undoubtedly mean:\nthat Washingtonians are entitled t<\nnational representation. His mes\nsage is a very strong indorsement o:\nthis inherent right and the peopli\nof Washington should be very happj\nwith this latest development. Witt\nthe backing of the President wi\nshould get national representation\nLet us all unite to attain this goal.'\nJames C. Wilkes, chairman of thi\nRepublican State Central Commit\ntee: \"The President's statement fol\nlow's closely the position that ou:\norganization has taken for a loni\ntime. The citizens of the Distric\nare entitled to the inherent righ\nof choosing their representatives ii\nCongress and of voting for Presi\ndent. The District should havi\nfull and complete suffrage, just a\nany other city.\u201d\nHarry S. Wender, former presi\ndent of the Federation of Citizens\nAssociations: \"President Truman i,\nto be congratulated for his state\nment. His years of residence heri\nas a Senator, Vice President, am\nnow President, have convinced hin\nthat the District is entitled to com\nplete suffrage in every respect.\u201d\nRobert E. Wise, president of thi\nJunior Board of Commerce: \u201cI an\ndelighted that the President ha\nseen fit to comment on a matte\nwhich has been of interest to thi\nJunior Board for more than H\nyears. I am pleased in this connec\ntion to have led the first forma\ndelegation to the Hill in support o\nthe Sumners-Capper resolution\nwhich is designed to provide a meas\nure of that self-government whicl\nMr. Truman advocates.\u201d\nJames S. Beattie, chairman of thi\nNational Representation Commit\ntee of Central Suffrage Confer\nence: \"-That the President, in sucl\nbusy times, has found time to de\nvote his attention to the District'\nsum age program snouia oe a sourc<\nof gratification to every one. Wi\nof the conference interpret Mr\nTruman's words to signify his sup\nport of the Sumners-Capper reso\nlution, passage of which we ari\ncurrently campaigning for.\u201d\nHugh Obear, president of the Dis\ntrict Bar Association: \"The Distric\nBar Association has always been ii\nfavor of full suffrage for Washing\nton. President Truman's clearcu\nstatement is very welcome, indeed\nIt is most heartening.\"\nMr. Hildreth, speaking as vici\nchairman of the Democratic Cen\ntral Committee of the District o\nColumbia: \"The President's recom\nmendation is the happiest thing w\nhave heard in years. It is the firs\ntime in history that a President'\nmessage has recommended to Con\ngress suffrage for the District. Thi\nmeans much for the success of ou\nmovement in the future. The suf\nfrage fight has been carried on fo\n150 years.\n\"President Truman was a mem\nber of the Platform Committee a\nthe Democratic National Conventioi\nin 1944, as a Senator from Missouri\nbefore he was even nominated to b\nVice President. He represented hi\nState on the committee. He partici\npated in the debate when the ques\ntion of the plank favoring votes fo\nthe District was under discussion\nHe took active part in supportin;\n1 the suffrage plank for the Nationa\nCapital.\n\u201cOne thing which impressed th\nMissouri Senator was the participa\nI tion of the District of Columbia ii\nthe war effort, especially in sendini\nits young men to fight, while havini\nnothing whatever to say about wh\nwas to become President, and Com\nmander in Chief of the arme<\nforces.\n\"When the poll tax States wer\ncomplaining before the committei\nj that they had to send their sons ti\nwar, and many were unable to vote\nit was pointed out to the committei\nwhen Senator Truman was presen\nthat this was exactly like the situa\ntion in the District of Columbia\nSenator Truman was keenly inter\nested in the platform committei\nsessions, and especially the debati\nover the District of Columbia. I\nwas not easy to get that Distric\nplank in. We had to fight for it\nSenator Truman voted in favor o\nthe plank. President Truman\u2019\nmessage to Congress is quite con\nsistent with the position Senato:\nTruman took as a member of th'\nDemocratic Platform Committee.\u201d\nNation Still Must Have\n2 Million in Service\nBy '47, Truman Says\nBy the Associated Press.\nTwo million men still must be\nunder arms when 1947 rolls around.\nPresident Truman told Congress1\ntoday of this estimate by the Army\n(;and Navy, and added that, if re\nj cruitlng can't produce that number\ni Congress should act, not later than\nI March, to extend the Draft Act.\nThe Chief Executive's message\ndispelled any idea that the 2,000,000\nman figure is a mere milepost in\ndemobilization, to be reached next\nJuly 1, with continued steady reduc\ntion of Army and Navy total\nI strength. But he did report that\nthe figure was \u2018\u2018above the ultimate\npeacetime level,\u201d a goal not yet\nannounced.\n\"The War and Navy Departments\nnow estimate that by a year from\nnow we will still need a strength of\nabout 2,000.000, including officers,\nfor the armed forces\u2014Army, Navy\nana air, Mr. iruman saia. i nave\nreviewed their estimates and believe\nthat the safety of the Nation will\nrequire maintenance of an armed\nstrength of this size for the caien\ndar year before us.\nMust Extend Draft.\n\u201cIn case the campaign for volun\nE teers does not produce that num\nt ber, it will be necessary by addi\ntional legislation to extend the Se\nlective Service Act beyond May 16,\nthe date of expiration under exist\ning law. That is the only way we\ncan get the men and bring back our\nveterans. There is no other way.\nAction along this line should not be\npostponed beyond March.\"\n<War Department planning\ncalls for about 1.500,000 men by\nnext July 1, the Navy 500,000 i\nThe President said the Army ob\ntained nearly 400,000 volunteers in\ni the past four months and the Navy\nt 80.000. (The Navy recently an\nnounced that up to January 1 it had\nreceived about 372.000 enlistees, new\nrecruits and transfers from the Na\nval Reserve. It is assumed the\nf President\u2019s figure referred to first\ni enlistments.)\nFull-Speed Demobilization.\nJ The Army and Navy demobiliza\ntion systems are \"working at full\nspeed,\" the President reported, but\nj observed: \"Of course there are cases\nof individual hardship in retention\nof personnel in the service. There\nwill be in the future. No system of\ni such size can operate to perfection.\"\nThe Army and Navy are expected\nj to spend $13,000,000,000 in the fiscal\nyear beginning next July 1. the\nj President said\u2014and he took this\noccasion to renew his recommenda\ntion for unification of the services.\nOf the total, the Army estimate\nis $8,000,000,000 and the Navy $5.\n000.000,000. This compares with an\nestimate for the current fiscal year\n1 of $28,000,000,000 for the Army and\n$14,700,000,000 for the Navy. The\npeak occurred in the last full fiscal\ni war year of 1945 when the Army\npaid out $50,339,372,369 and the\nNavy $30,047,152,135. The President\nexplained that detailed estimates\nfor the services would be submitted\nthis spring.\n10 Per Cenl of Income.\nThe $13,000,000,000 for the armed\nforces is out of an estimated total\nof $15,000,000,000 for war liquidation,1\nfor occupation and for national de\nfense.\nTerming thi* \"a large sum for a\nyear which begins 10 months after\nfighting has ended.\" the President\nadded that \u2018'it is 10 times our ex\npenditure for defense before the\nwar: it amounts to about 10 per\nI cent of our expected national in\ncome.\"\n\"The large expenditures needed\nfor our national defense emphasize\n1 the great scope for effective organ\ni ization in furthering economy and\nefficiency. To this end I have re\ncently recommended to the Con\nligress adoption of legislation com\ni bining the War and Navy depart\nrments into a single Department of\nNational Defense.\"\ni As an example of the cost of liqui\ndation, there was the President's\nestimate of the bill for mustering\nI out pay\u2014$2,500,000,000 for the pres\nent fiscal year 1946 and about $500,\n000.000 in the coming year.\nPolicy of UNO Support.\nIt will be the policy of the United\nStates, he added, to \"foster, support\nand develop the United Nations\nOrganization in its purpose of pre\nventing international war.\"\nIn connection with his discussion\nI of UNO he referred to the proposal\nfor an international commission to\nexplore effective control of the\natom bomb and atomic energy and\nsaid:\n\"I have great hope for the de\nvelopment of mutually effective\nsafeguards whcih wull permit the\nfullest international control of this\nnew atomic force.\n\u201cI believe it is possible that ef\nfective means can be developed\nthrough the United Natons Organi\nzation to prohibit, outlaw and pre\nvent the use of atomic energy for\ndestructive purposes.\"\nj Patterson in Frankfurt\nFRANKFURT, Jan. 21 (/PI.\u2014iSec\nretary of War Patterson arrived to\nt day from India.\n5\nrj\nr\nt!\n'J\n5\n\n\nl\n1\nr\nARTHRITIS\nNEURITIS\nDon\u2019t neglect painful\nmuscles, aching joints and\nthrobbing nerves. Many\ndoctors prescribe n a\nture\u2019s soothing aid.\nMOUNTAIN VALLEY\nfrom HOT SPRINGS, Ark.\nMINERAL WATER\nphone for a case\nME. 1062\n904 12th Sh N.W.\nSnyder Gives Warning.\nInflation Must Be Met\nBy Price Controls\nBy the Associated Press. (j\nReconversion Director John W. r\nSnyder declared today the threat of t\ninflation mast be met by price con- v\ntrols and rising production to head c\noff an \"economic Pearl Harbor.\u201d c\nProduction for civilian use al- C\nready is at an annual rate $20,000,\n0C0.000 greater than four months ago, t\nMr. Snyder said in a year-end re- t\nport to the President and Congress, i\nBut the time cannot be foretold now t\nwhen industry will come abreast of r\nthe soaring public demand for\ngoods, he added.\nMr. Snyder urged strongly that the\nPrice Control Act be extended be-\nyond its scheduled midyear expira- t\ntion date, saying: j;\n\"it would be foolhardy not to i\nrecognize that the excess of demand j)\nover supply throughout the eco- j)\nnomic system may continue far be- i\nyond June 30.\u201d ;c\nPeaks Early This Spring. j\nUUUIlipiUJ U1V.UK UUU limaviumu\npressure may hit their peaks simul-!\ntaneously early this spring. Mr.\nSnyder said. However, joblessness t\nwill be below former estimates. It j\nnow is around 3,000,000. compared t\nwith the 5,000,000 or 6,000.000 Gov- t\nernment agencies had expected.\n\"The basic need at this particular\ntime to meet both situations is more r\nproduction,\" the reconversion di- r\nrector declared.\n\"We must race to expand our out\nput. We must smother inflation\nwith a steady stream of goods. We\nmust speed up the wheels of in\ndustry to create the jobs our work\ners and veterans need.\"\nLabor strife delayed the start of\nsome important production lines, he\nsaid, but high output of cars, re\nfrigerators, washing machines and\nother durable goods \"could not have\nbeen achieved by this time, in any\ncase.\"\nForecasts for 1946.\nThe report forecast what 1946;\nwould bring in these vital fields:\nFood\u2014Americans may eat more\nthan in the record year 1944, when\nconsumption was 11 per cent above\nthe prewar average.\nHousign\u2014\"Our most serious short\nage.\" Private building will start\n\"the fastest upswing in its history,\u201d;\nbut demand will be several times\ngreater than the new construction\nsupplied.\nJobs\u2014Business cannot expand\nquickly enough to absorb in the\nnear future the 4.500,000 veterans to\nbe freed in the next half year, along\nwith newly discharged Government\nand war plant workers.\nCoal\u2014\"Supply prospects are fair\u201d;\nClothing\u2014Shortages will perisist.;\nDemand for cotton goods will top f\nsupply by 20 to 50 per cent.\nTrade\u2014May double the 1939 total\nof $40,000,000,000 in sales, and thus\nfar exceed the 1945 record.\nPayments to Farmers.\nAutomobiles The industry ex\npected \"before the strike\u201d to make\n4.000.000 cars this year, and has laid\nthe physical basis for such a volume, j\ntopped only in 1929.\nAgriculture\u2014To safeguard farm\nincome, Congress should authorize\n\"direct payments to farmers where\nnecessary\u201d instead of the present\nmethod of supporting prices.\nMore food will be available this\nyear than last, but shortages will\npersist through the early months\nat least on butter, sugar, pork,\ncanned fish and the better grades\nof beef and veal.\nMr. Snyder plumped strongly for\nthe so-called \"full employment\u201d\nbill extension of the Second War\nPowers Act.\nUnless the war powers legislation j\nis prolonged beyond June 30. he as\nserted. the Government will be\nstripped of its ability to break in-1\ndustrial bottlenecks, fight shortages\nand speed construction.\nAnd, he added, \"the priorities we\nhave established for veterans ion\nhousing) will become meaningless at\nthe very time they are most urgent\nly needed.\"\nPearl Harbor\nContinued Prom First Page.)\nstages of the war, when faster ves\nsels were available, he explained\nAdmiral Kimmel also testified the\nJapanese made their \"greatest mis\ntake\u201d by attacking the American\nfleet at Pearl Harbor and failing to\nput the base itself out of commis\nsion\nHe said it tvas probable no attack\nwould have been attempted if the\nAmerican ships had been sent back\nto the West Coast.\nMeanwhile. Committee Counsel\nSeth W. Richardson promised a\nsearching inquiry into the \"lost\"\nwar warning which the late Secre\ntary of the Navy Knox was reported\nto have said he sent to the Pacific\nFleet on December 6, 1941. the day\nbefore the attack.\nMurphy Asks More Details.\nRepresentative Murphy, Democrat,\nof Pennsylvania asked counsel to go\nfurther into it this morning, after\nit had been mentioned for the first\ntime Saturday.\nAdmiral Kimmel testified Satur\nday that Secretary Knox, on his visit\nto Hawaii a few days after the at-f\n\nick, said he had sent such a mes\nige. Admiral Kimmel said he had\not received such a message.\nAdmiral Kimmel told Representa\nive Gearhart that even if no dam\nge had been done to the fleet at\nearl Harbor, \u201cit would have been\nisastrous\" to send that fleet to the\nelief of the Philippines, because at\nbat time a train of supply ships\n'as not then available to transport\nil and other material to the fleet\nver a great distance of the Pacific\nicean.\nMr. Gearhart then sought to show\nbat if the fleet had been kept on j\nbe West Coast of the United States\n1 1941, the Japs would have found;\nbe task of trying to immobilize it\nlore difficult.\ni\nTwo Advantages Cited.\nAdmiral Kimmel cited two ad\nantages on protecting the fleet on\nhe West Coast, namely, more ports\na which to maneuver and a smaller\nrea requiring air patrol. On the\nVest Coast, he said, the fleet would\niave had the mainland behind it,\nsaving only an arc of 180 degrees\nver the ocean requiring air patrol,\nit Pearl Harbor, he said, effective\nir reconnaissance required patrol\nf the whole circle of 360 degrees.\nMr. Gearhart said it was specula\nte whether the Japs would have i\nttacked the fleet on the West Coast,!\nut added, \u201cthey did many foolish\nhings during the war, including the\nttack on Pearl Harbor.\u201d\n\"I think that was the greatest i\nlistake they made,\u201d Admiral Kim- i\nlel replied.\nRepresentative Gearhart noted\n.hat Admiral Kimmel s predecessor,\n\\dmiral J. O. Richardson, had\nsought unsuccessfully to take his\nships back to the West Coast to pre\naare them for war. but was told\nay Washington officials that the\nfleet was to be kept in Hawaii as a\ndeterrent to Japanese aggressive\nmoves.\nWill Seek Information.\nMr. Richardson said regarding\nthe \"lost\" war warning that he un\nderstood Mr. Knox was supposed to\nhave told two officers attached to\nthe Secretary's office that he had\nwritten such a message December 6.\n1941, the day before Pearl Harbor\nwas bombed. They were named as\nRear Admiral Prank E. Beatty and\nMarine Capt. John H. Dillon.\n\u201cI think when I have talked to\nBeatty and Dillon we will have all\nthe information available,\u201d Mr.\nRichardson told the committee.\n\"However, I will try to find out\nwhether there is a stenographer who\nmight have taken the message or\nany one else who might know\nsomething about it.\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019d like to request that any in\nformation about a so-called lost\nmessage alleged to have been sent\nthe night of December 6 be re\nported to this committee,\u201d said Mr.\nMurphy. \u201cI\u2019d like to know the\nfacts.\u201d\n\u201cAll I know is what the Congress\nman heard about a conversation\noetween Mr Knox and Admiral\nKimmel said Mr. Richardson, \u201cbut\nwe will try to find out if there 13\nany more information available.\u201d\nWe have a new and tested plan of automo\nbile financing which we believe offers the\ngreatest convenience and advantages to pros\npective car buyers. Inquiries are welcomed.\n1700 Eye St. N.W. mE. 3996\n4% LOANS I\non Life Insurance\nPolicy Cash Values\nUtilize this service\u2014to refinance an existing\nindebtedness or to provide additional funds.\nThe plan is simply this:\nAn assignment of the policy is made to the hank, a\nnote for the desired amount is executed (limited to\nthe cash value of the policy), and you pay interest\nof $10 every three months for each one thousand\ndollars borrowed. Inquiries invited.\nBank of Commerce Savings\nMain Office Branch\n7th E Sts. N.W. H ot No. Capitol\n\u25a0SPECIALISTS IN LIFE INSURANCE LOANS\u201d\n\u00bb_\nThe Month's Most Interesting and\nImportant Articles -\u2014-gg^>.\nI by HENRY WALLACE\nm These jobs are not mythical, says\nHenry Wallace. They are in the\ncensus. Here is a forthright an\nswcr to all who have challenged\nthe man who first projected the\nidea of sixty million jobs.\nFEBRUARY'S\nAlso f\u00abi This hsuo Artklos by\nif Walter Lippmann\nArthur Krock\nDorothy Thompson\nH. I. Phillips\nDonald R. Richborg\nk","height":"31516","width":"22196"}}
